					   <td>

			
			
			


<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="100%">
<tr>
	<td width="1%">&nbsp;</td>
	<td width="98%">

		<table width="100%">
		<tr>
			<td>
				<p>
					<font face="verdana" size="3"><b>    Demetrii Spiritdrinker's Erudite Necromancer Guide</b></font>
					<br>
					<font face="verdana" size="2">
					<b><A href="mailto:VoraciousApathy@aol.com">Demetrii Spiritdrinker</a> | 
		            11/9/2001 2:37:04 PM</b></font></p>
		         <a href="guides.asp">
		         <font face="verdana" size="2">Return to guide listing.</font></a>
					
					<p>
					<font face="verdana" size="2">The Erudite's Guide to the Pursuit of Necromancy<BR>
<BR>
- by Demetrii Spiritdrinker -<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
Guide Information Summary<BR>
( Read me first, you jerks. )<BR>
<BR>
	This guide shall be done in the style that the ' Revised Wizard's Guide ', created by Hobono, was.. <BR>
<BR>
That is to say, this is an extremely detailed guide that's basically going to serve as a walkthrough for this particular race/class/deity combination. Note that many of the tactics listed, and hunting grounds specified, will be hunted by other classes.. and, indeed, any kind of necromancer will probably find several things that'll help them out.. after all, a dark elf could take the time to go to any of the hunting grounds listed, and employ the same tactics, right? <BR>
<BR>
Necromancer factions don't really have a wide range of differences.. the gnomes get the best faction.. but, let's face it: Gnomes just don't intimidate people as easily. I, for one, am inclined to laugh hysterically until I turn red in the face, and collapse, quite unceremoniously, whenever I see a gnome walk up to me in a black robe.<BR>
<BR>
Some might argue this point, saying things like.. ' .. but Demetrii! Gnomes have style! &quot;<BR>
<BR>
... Good point. Counterpoint.<BR>
<BR>
&quot; ... You're an idiot. &quot;<BR>
<BR>
Gnomes don't have ' style '. Not even in the most remote sense of the word. Gnomes are tiny. Their robes look stupid. They have big noses, and resemble old midgets. Old midgets possess no style.. therefore, neither do Gnomes.<BR>
<BR>
Racial prejudices, and obvious facts aside.. This guide was built primarily for the newbie Erudite necromancer, who has no idea as to what to do, and what goals to work towards. I'm not going to include a table of contents. That'd require extra organization on my part, and I'm notoriously disorganized.. so, I'll make up an excuse as to why I'm not going to put the effort into making said table of contents..<BR>
<BR>
... I spent hours and hours making this guide, and if I gave you a table of contents, you'd probably just skip right to the information you wanted, and then you'd close this guide out. That wouldn't do. I want you to print this out. Staple the pages together, in order, and set it next to your keyboard. This way, you'll be able to refer to it easily, while playing.<BR>
<BR>
Now that I've explained myself, and likely discouraged those of you who are my intellectual inferiors.. <BR>
Guide On. <BR>
<BR>
Level 1: The Induction into Apprenticeship<BR>
<BR>
Hunting Ground: Paineel Newbie Garden<BR>
<BR>
Targets: Decaying Skeletons, Fire Beetles ( Level 2+ ), Pack Rats, Black Bats, Undead Rats ( Level 3+ )<BR>
<BR>
MustKill NPC: Noclin's Pet ( Level 4+ )<BR>
After murdering Noclin's Pet, loot the Femur, and hand it over to Noclin Saah. He'll give you a sweet staff that's useful up to about level 16.<BR>
<BR>
__________________________________________________<BR>
<BR>
Well, here you are.. You've just created an Erudite Necromancer. You're marveling at your ridiculously high base intelligence.. (If you didn't boost it all the way to 142, then delete the character, and start over)<BR>
What now?<BR>
<BR>
I'll tell you what now. Go into your inventory.. not by clickin' yer little class symbol. Thas' how newbies do it. Press the ' I ' key on your keyboard. Now then.. put the dagger in yer primary weapon slot, and run over to your guild mistress. I'm not going to tell you how to get to her.. she is inside the Abatoir, top floor. Get a friggin' map. Now, then. Put on that ugly robe she gives you, and put one point into piercing. Save the rest. Extra points are always useful.<BR>
<BR>
Now.. go back to the newbie gardens. Murder rats, and bats, and decaying skeletons. The spells you should have at the moment, unless you're a twink.. ( ... and chances are, your not ... else you'd probably know enough about the game to play a necromancer ... ) are..<BR>
<BR>
__________________________________________________<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
Lifetap, Minor Shielding<BR>
<BR>
&quot; D00d, these spells suck. &quot;<BR>
<BR>
Yeah, they do. Your level one, stop whining. Murder more stuff, and conserve the bonechips. Trust me, a few dozen levels from now.. you'd kill someone for a stack of them. Fascination with human remains begins early, so start hoarding those chunks of precious organic calcium!<BR>
<BR>
Once you've got about five gold, and you've hit Level 2, run back to your guild, and buy the spells: <BR>
<BR>
__________________________________________________<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
Cavorting Bones, Locate Corpse<BR>
<BR>
... and, scribe them, and memorize them, and then run back to the gardens. Using one of the bonechips in your inventory ... ( ... if you didn't listen to me, and decided to sell them instead ... :: backhands the contrary reader :: ... start listening. I don't just tell you to do things to inconvenience you. ), cast Cavorting Bones. <BR>
<BR>
It might fizzle once or twice, but when it goes off, hold still. Green haze will flow outta yer fingers, and when the spell fires, one bone chip will disappear from your inventory. The result of this ' used ' bone chip is a skeleton. This skeleton is Level 1 -every- time, and he hits for a maximum, unarmed damage of 10. Hey, seeing as how he can take one or two hits that would've hit you instead if you have to run, and seeing as how that'll be extra damage during combat.. fights'll end that much faster.<BR>
<BR>
Now, then. A quick lesson in pet control. Make the following hotkeys:<BR>
<BR>
/pet health report<BR>
/pet kill<BR>
/pet back off<BR>
/pet guard here<BR>
<BR>
Create a hotkey by going to the ' Socials ' menu, on the far right of your screen, and right-clicking one of the buttons.. click on the text, and replace it with one of the commands listed above. Rename the hotkey by clicking the little name of the hotkey, on the same screen that you replaced the old text with the pet command. <BR>
<BR>
Once this is done, left-click the new hotkey, and hold down the clicker. A big, square button will appear on your cursor. Move this button to one of the slots on the far left, and click. The hotkey'll be installed there.. to use a hotkey without clicking it, look at the number keys on the top of your keyboard. Keys 1 - 0 correspond to Hotkeys 1 - 10. Hotkeys are counted in a left to right fashion.. so, if you wanna hit the hotkey right below hotkey 1, you press 3. The one below hotkey three, you press 5.. next to five, you press 6, etc.<BR>
<BR>
Make whatever hotkeys you want. My pet commands are as follows:<BR>
Hotkey 7: Pet Kill<BR>
Hotkey 8: Pet Back Off<BR>
Hotkey 9: Pet Health Report<BR>
<BR>
... for the commands ,' Pet Guard Here '... ' Pet Sit Down ' ... ' Pet Follow Me ' ... I just type 'em in.<BR>
<BR>
Anyway, with your pet, kill fire beetles, skeletons, bats, and rats. Avoid Undead Rats, and avoid Noclin's Pet. The rats're nasty at Level 1-3 ... and the Pet could kick your butt without breakin' a sweat.<BR>
<BR>
I'm not really going to detail the ascension from Level 1 - 3. You are fighting in the same spot, and these levels fly by, anyway. Save -all- your money.. pay -just- enough to purchase food. <BR>
<BR>
__________________________________________________<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
Level 4: Neophyte<BR>
Skill Available: Meditate<BR>
Meditation allows you to regenerate mana at a super-accelerated rate. Never sit down to regain mana. Always, always meditate. Put one practice point into Meditation, and save the others.<BR>
<BR>
Hunting Grounds: Paineel Newbie Gardens, The Warrens<BR>
<BR>
Targets: Decaying Skeletons, Rats, Bats, Undead Rats, Noclin's Pet<BR>
<BR>
Fear - This is an -essential- spell in a necromancer's arsenal. You'll be using this -consistently- when soloing. Basically, this spell makes a monster turn tail, and flee from you and your pet. Note that a monster that is chasing after you only takes 66% of a DoTs normal damage. However, an NPC that is standing still, or running away from you takes full damage. This spell will last for a maximum of 18 seconds. It is very expensive to cast at this level, taking about a bubble of mana.. but, by about Level 12 or 16, when ' Fearkiting ' becomes truly effective, you'll be able to cast this spell non-stop, pretty much. May as well buy it now.<BR>
<BR>
Leering Corpse - Generates a skeletal fighter, Level 3 to 5. This pet is capable of Bashing, which interrupts a creature's spellcasting, and adds a bit of extra damage..( anywhere from 1-6 points,right now )<BR>
This pet has, at the most, 90 points of health. Don't let it tank. Stick your damage over time spells on a creature, and then get into melee range. It's a much tougher pet than the old summons, but it's not a match for a creature of equal level.<BR>
<BR>
Clinging Darkness - This spell deals 30 points of damage in 36 seconds, 5 points at a time. It also makes a creature run 24% faster, and the slow-down, or ' snare ' effect increases with your level, eventually maxing out at a 30% movement rate reduction. <BR>
<BR>
Lifespike - A much more effective, more efficient upgrade to Lifetap. This spell deals 9 points of damage, and heals you for 9 points of health. Just like other spells in the Lifedrain line, this one gets better as you rise in levels, eventually maxing out at 11 points of drain, and damage.<BR>
<BR>
Poison Bolt - Your nastiest damage over time spell, and one that you're going to be using for a long, long time. Fast-acting, like all poison-based DoT spells, this one does 6 points of damage initially, and then hits the creature for another 6 points of damage, every six seconds, for 42 seconds. The spell deals 42 points of damage, counting the initial direct-damage.<BR>
<BR>
Gate - This is a must-have spell, albeit a bit difficult to find. Ask around, and someone'll probably lead you to the vendor. I forgot who sold it, but it -is- sold in Paineel.. I think one of the robed guys just outside the door that leads to your guildmistress sells this, along with the shielding spells.<BR>
<BR>
__________________________________________________<BR>
<BR>
Sure, you can buy the others for this level.. an' mebe even the Level 1 spells you didn't get. I mean, Siphon Strength is kinda nice.. makes the monsters hit ya for less damage, an' gives ya 10 points of strength when it's maxed out.. but, it isn't necessary. It's hard to notice the difference, and it wears off quickly.<BR>
<BR>
Poison Bolt and Clinging Darkness, on the other hand, will -rape- things. Let's explain the nature of these spells.<BR>
<BR>
__________________________________________________<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
...I cover my foes in dots...<BR>
<BR>
You cast Poison Bolt.. and it nails something for - 6 - damage. You're thinking.. ' that sucks ... '<BR>
<BR>
What you might not know is the ' behind the scenes ' damage this spell, and others, do. Time to get aqquainted with the Tick! <BR>
<BR>
A ' Tick ' is a universally understood time-incriment. At least, in EQ. It lasts exactly six seconds, and it's how often the server refreshes the monster's health information, as well as how often the server applies a bit of Damage over Time. You see, when you cast Poison Bolt, it initially hit the creature for 6. However, every six seconds, it'll hit the creature again for about 5 damage. It'll do this every six seconds, until the spell wears off.. and once the spell is stuck on the creature, it has no chance to resist the damage each 6 seconds.. basically, once it's stuck to your target.. unless the target is chasing you.. it'll take full damage until the duration of the spell is reached. Poison Bolt lasts 42 seconds, so it hits the creature seven times for 5 damage each time.. plus, the first 6 damage. -Not- bad, eh? <BR>
<BR>
We necromancers are the masters of Damage over Time. Wizards do it quick, we do it slow.. but, we do it much more efficiently.. and, besides.. deathmages have style. <BR>
<BR>
Learn, right now, that your spells will almost always take around a minute or two to dump every last point of damage into a creature, and you'll be happy later on.. of course, you might be wondering.. <BR>
<BR>
' ...but our pet can't last that long, if he is constantly being clobbered by my target.. he dies before it does! '<BR>
<BR>
Easily solved. Reverse-kite. Wizards and druids, and many others have mastered a tactic called ' kiting '. This involves getting Spirit of the Wolf cast on you, so that you can outrun a creature.. and then pissing a creature off with a direct damage, or snare spell. Now, the monster is chasing you, albeit injured, or slowly. From long distance, the caster begins to throw damage spells at the creature, and then running away before it can get in range to hit said caster. <BR>
<BR>
Necromancers have a much better, more refined, and infinitely more dignified way to kill. Reverse-kiting.<BR>
<BR>
You get your very first Darkness spell at Level 4. Clinging Darkness.<BR>
<BR>
While it sucks compared to the Level 12, 29, and 49, and 50+ versions.. it does it's job nicely at Level 4, and it's pretty cheap to cast. Clinging Darkness basically makes solid strands of shadow wrap around a creature's body like a net, slowing it down so it can't run as quickly. It also does about 30 damage over about 30 seconds or so.. so, combined with Poison Bolt and a pet, as well as your new Drain spell.. you'll easily be finishing things off.<BR>
<BR>
' Why make it run slowly? It's not hitting me.. it's hitting my pet! '<BR>
<BR>
Not for long. Cast Fear. Fear will make the creature turn around, and flee from your pet. Note that, with darkness, it runs slowly. Note, also, that if a creature is running -away- from you, it still takes full damage from your DoTs( Damage over Time spells ).<BR>
<BR>
This means your pet is outrunning the creature, and hitting it in the back.. and it isn't fighting back.<BR>
<BR>
Thus, you now know how to keep a creature from eating your skeleton, and then you. <BR>
<BR>
Murder everything in the newbie garden that cons blue, until you are Level 7. At Level 7, go and buy some cloth armor with all the money you've been saving up.. then, go to the Warrens. <BR>
<BR>
You can fight in this Kobold-Filled, Train-Infested dungeon all the way up to about Level 25... but it sucks, and I wouldn't recommend it. Fight here until you've gotten..<BR>
<BR>
__________________________________________________<BR>
<BR>
Level 8: Senior Apprentice<BR>
<BR>
Hunting Grounds: The Warrens ( Not Recommended ), Qeynos Hills, Blackburrow<BR>
<BR>
Targets: Assorted Kobolds, Gnolls, Grizzly Bears, Rabid Wolves, Rabid Grizzly Bears<BR>
<BR>
Bone Walk - Generates a Level 7-9 skeletal fighter, which hits harder than the Level 4 summons, and naturally has much more health. This pet can take a licking, so don't be afraid to let it melee a creature for a little while. Keep track of it's health with ' pet health report ', and if it drops to 30% or so, go ahead and get into melee range, clobbering the creature with your staff until it dies. This pet has roughly 200 health, and hits for 14 points of damage when the spell creates the highest level pet possible. The pet's bash has also increased, in both frequency of usage, and damage. Occasionally, it'll bash for 8.<BR>
<BR>
Dark Empathy - A reverse lifedrain, this acts as a healing spell. It drains you of 30 points of health, and heals your target for that much. Cast this on a tank your grouped with, and then Lifedrain the health back. Rinse and repeat.<BR>
<BR>
Dark Pact - The first in a long line of deliciously wonderful, necromancer-only spells. This spell begins to drain you of health by about 4 points, standing up. However, for every 4 points of health drained..<BR>
and, by the way, it's only 2 points sitting.. you regenerate an extra 2 points of mana, essentially making you meditate about 20% faster. Keep it on constantly. It doesn't really hurt all that much, and the mana regeneration it bestows is equal to the Level 16 enchanter spell, Breeze.. only, you get it at Level 8.<BR>
<BR>
Deadeye - Yet another awsome spell. This gives you the ability to see perfectly well in the middle of the night.. and, it also allows you to see invisible things.. like that wizard sneaking up behind you, thinking he's slick.<BR>
<BR>
Gather Shadows - Self-only invisibility. We get alot of self-only spells.. it stems from a lack of caring about whether or not other people have an easy time overcoming obstacles. With necromancer's, its almost always ' me, me, me '.<BR>
<BR>
Lesser Shielding - A welcome upgrade to Minor Shielding.. Lesser Shielding increases your magic resistance by a bit more, and raises your health and armor class by much, much more than Minor Shielding. Like all other forms of shielding, keep this on you at all times. There isn't a reason not to.<BR>
<BR>
Mend Bones - This is like Dark Empathy for your pet. It works on all undead, so you could heal someone elses pet ... but remember ... ' me, me, me '. The nice thing about this spell is that it not only heals for 50, instead of 30 ... but, it also doesn't injure you to do it ... and, it doesn't build aggro, either.<BR>
<BR>
Ward Undead - Hey, save yourself the trouble I went through. Get this spell, put a practice point into Evocation, and start casting this on your pet, to raise your skill. This line of spells gets to be pretty devestating. Heck, this one shoots an undead creature for 41 points of damage, when its reached its full potential.<BR>
<BR>
Shadowstep - Used mainly in duels, it really annoys warriors. Basically, this spell transports you in a random direction, for a random distance.. for 10 mana, and a 1 second casting time. Basically, ' now you see me, now you don't. ' Cheap enough to chain-cast, it really rains on a fighter's parade during a duel. Use it frequently, teleporting out of range of his sword or axe, and casting a spell on him or her, then teleporting again. And so on, and so forth.<BR>
<BR>
__________________________________________________<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
The Warrens is still capable of giving you good experience.. but, frankly, the bad pathing and constant trains make it pretty crappy at Level 8. Thus, you should cast Gather Shadows, your self-only invisibility spell, and run to Erudin.. Run to the Erudin docks, and wait for the boat.<BR>
<BR>
When the boat arrives, hop on. Ride the boat til it gets to a place called Qeynos.. however, leap into the water as soon as the docks are in sight. The people of Qeynos hate you. The guards will murder you if they see you.<BR>
<BR>
Welcome to your new home.<BR>
<BR>
Swimming underwater, and taking the time to come up for air now and then.. you'll eventually come upon a sort of.. hole under a dock, underwater. Get a breath of air, and swim down the hole. You'll zone into the Catacombs. Swim through the tunnel, until you find a spot where you can come up for air. Get a map of the Catacombs, and make your way out of them, exiting through the hole that leads to the secret North Qeynos entrance. Promptly get someone to cast Bind Affinity on you.. <BR>
<BR>
( ... that makes it so that when you cast Gate, you'll return to the spot you were standing when they cast bind ... instead of popping up in Paineel, and having to take the dumb boat back again. )<BR>
<BR>
Now, then. Get directions to Blackburrow, and sneak around, invisible. Scout around the place, and eventually settle down in the ' Rest Area '. Just ask people to show you to it. <BR>
<BR>
Make a pet, and go through the dungeon, shooting a gnoll with a poison bolt, and running back to your pet, to fight the gnoll at the rest area.<BR>
<BR>
Note that gnolls are just like kobolds. If the one you attacked runs by another one, the other one will attack you to. Be careful with your pulls, and let your pet take the heat if you pull a train, so that you'll have a chance to escape. <BR>
<BR>
Go ahead and start asking around for cheap intelligence boosting items. The more intelligence you have, the more mana. Also, when meditating, be sure to cast Dark Pact.<BR>
<BR>
__________________________________________________<BR>
<BR>
Level 12: Acolyte of Fear<BR>
<BR>
Hunting Grounds: Highpass<BR>
<BR>
Targets: Group for ' the Gnoll Gate '<BR>
<BR>
Heat Blood - The Damage-Dealing DoT you'll be using for quite a long time. Vicious indeed, this spell does a total of 170 points of damage, 17 points at a time. Nearly unresistable, it is expensive.. but well worth the cost in mana.<BR>
Leach - This spell has the same resistance rate as your Lifedrain spells.. which is to say, assuming the creature is not more than six levels above you.. this spell will affect them in a negative way. This spell is like a slow, but extremely effective Lifedrain. Every six seconds, it strikes a creature for 11, and heals you for 11, in addition to natural healing.. ( 1 standing, 2 sitting )Combined with Dark Pact, and this spell, the damage your mana converter deals to you is easily offset.<BR>
Engulfing Darkness - Banish Clinging Darkness. This spell is far superior. Clinging Darkness slowed a creature's running speed by 30%.. Engulfing Darkness slows a creature by 45%. It also deals a total of 110 points of damage. Used primarily in Fearkiting, and Grouping, this spell is wonderful. Keep it memorized.<BR>
<BR>
Lifedraw - A HUGE upgrade to Lifespike.. Lifedraw drains 39 points of health, and gives it to you. Sick, sick, sick. It'll heal about a bubble of Health, and maxes out for 45 damage. <BR>
<BR>
Convoke Shadow - Generates a Level 9 - 11 skeletal warrior, that has about 350 points of health. It bashes for about 10, and hits for a maximum of 16. Nice.<BR>
<BR>
Bind Affinity - Bind Affinity means you can go places. Casting this spell alters the destination of your gate spell. You can bind yourself anywhere, but other people can only be bound in cities, and certain zones. It also changes the spot you pop up at when you die. Don't die, though. That's counter-productive.<BR>
<BR>
Endure Disease - Cast it on yourself, and your pet, and the enemy disease spells have much less chance of sticking.<BR>
<BR>
Scent of Dusk - This one lowers fire, poison, and disease resistance on a target by 7 - 9. Not really useful at this level, seeing as how you aren't using any disease or poison spells, and Heatblood almost never gets resisted.. still, the higher-level versions have their uses.<BR>
<BR>
__________________________________________________<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
You have graduated. You have become a true necromancer, and as such, your tactics must change. Crude and ineffective, you managed to get the job done through the use of brute force, and weak spells. You have attained your goal, however, and the time for getting your hands dirty is behind you.<BR>
<BR>
&quot; Demetrii, I was grouped.. and I threw all three of my DoTs at a creature. It immediately attacked me, and no one could get it off! I died, lost level 12, my wife left me, my house burned down, I went bankrupt, the stock market crashed, and someone ate my last Tictac! Not only is my breath no longer minty fresh, but I'm without my cool new DoTs! Boohoo, boohoo. &quot;<BR>
<BR>
New tactics come into play. Learn them from me, because I learned them the hard way.<BR>
<BR>
Just as a wizard must wait for the right moment to throw a blast, a necromancer must learn to carefully stack damage over time spells. Just putting them on, one after the other, as fast as you can, isn't the way.<BR>
<BR>
Using anything besides Darkness in a group that kills creatures before your damage over time spells wear off is a waste of mana, anyway. <BR>
<BR>
You see, we're all about efficiency. If our spell isn't going through for full, then why bother casting it? In big groups, simply throw Darkness at a creature. It'll do damage, and so will your pet. Feel free to Lifedrain for extra damage.. but for the most part, meditate. Darkness serves another purpose.. when monsters get low on health, they ussually turn around and run away. Whereas running slowly away could allow the monster to call its friends, darkness prevents it from running at all. The creature simply stands there, and gets whacked.<BR>
<BR>
Use Heatblood when soloing, and use Leach when you are low on health, and want to mana convert. Otherwise, Engulfing and a pet will do the trick.<BR>
<BR>
Also, when soloing, it is important to take courses in..<BR>
<BR>
__________________________________________________<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
Anger Management<BR>
<BR>
Monsters have a ' hatelist '. Just like Santa Claus. Basically, when you and your group, or pet, annoy a monster, it writes your names down. Your goal is to stay at the bottom of that list.<BR>
<BR>
Monsters hate whoever is doing the most damage.. they also hate everyone else who hurt them, but they'll deal with them later. Monsters focus on the one they hate. <BR>
<BR>
Stacking numerous DoTs at once really ticks a creature off.. so, don't do it. Practice some friggin' restraint, and let the group, or your pet, build ' aggro ' with the creature, before you start nailing it with every spell in the book. Remember, we might look snazzy in a black robe, but we're still as frail as toothpicks if we're the ones being focused on. Can't cast a spell if a gnoll's fist is slapping you in the side of the head every two seconds.<BR>
<BR>
__________________________________________________<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
Highpass<BR>
<BR>
I'm going to tell you how to go to Highpass in ... relative ... detail. <BR>
<BR>
Go to Qeynos Hills, and follow the road. Take your first right, and zone into West Karana. Follow the road until you leave the canyon. <BR>
<BR>
Follow the canyon wall that goes off to your right, until you reach the bank of a river. There'll be a barbarian fishing village. Avoid them, they probably hate you anyway. Remaining invisible, follow the river forward, keeping the village behind you. You'll zone into North Karana after a loooong time.<BR>
<BR>
Keep following the river, passing a stone bridge, and a group of raiders. Eventually, you'll reach a wooden bridge. Cross it, and follow the road until it branches right, and left. Hang a right, and keep following the path, recasting Gather Shadows as needed. Avoid the NPCs.. you're a necromancer, and everyone hates your guts.<BR>
<BR>
The path ends at the foot of a canyon, with a winding path going up the side of the mountain. Follow it up for quite awhile, and you'll zone into Highpass.<BR>
<BR>
Your goal is to find the gnoll, and orc gates. Ask around, everyone knows where they are. Once you've done this your goal is to murder gnoll after gnoll until the Highpass guards stop hating you. Once you're   ' glowered at ', give the Captain standing near the gnoll gate all the ' gnoll scalps ' you've been collecting, to raise your faction with the merchants.<BR>
<BR>
Remain here til Level 16. At 16, you'll be able to fight effectively at the Orc gate.<BR>
<BR>
__________________________________________________<BR>
<BR>
Level 16: Bonecaller<BR>
<BR>
Essential Skill Available: Research<BR>
Researching is the process of collecting certain scraps of paper, called ' words ', placing them in a Book of Dark Bindings in the proper amounts, and pressing the combine button, in the hopes of creating a spell that isn't buyable in stores. Save every practice point you have, and whenever you level up, dump them all into Researching. You'll be happier in the long run. <BR>
<BR>
Hunting Grounds: Highpass<BR>
<BR>
Targets: Gnolls, and Orcs<BR>
<BR>
Heart Flutter: Wow, does this spell annoy a monster. It builds -massive- amounts of aggro, due to the rather nasty effects it bestows upon a creature. In fights with orcs, you may want to throw this, and engulfing darkness. Just be careful to space the spells far apart, so that you aren't aggro'd, and murdered. This spell is disease-based, and does get resisted much more frequently than Heat Blood.. yet less frequently than darkness. It lowers a creature's strength by up to 20 points, and knocks 17 points of AC off of them. It also does 144 points of damage. If it goes through, the creature is significantly weakened.<BR>
<BR>
Feign Death: A must-have spell, this allows you to play 'dead'. When the spell is cast, creatures attacking you believe you've died, and wander away, having forgotten about you. There is a chance that their             ' hatelist ' is cleared. If it hasn't been cleared, however, the moment you stand up.. you'll be re-aggro'd. Just recast it, until it works. It's a definite lifesaver, even if it doesn't clear the hatelist. If the monster forgets about you for the moment, it gives your group, and your pet a chance to murder the offending nasty.<BR>
<BR>
Hungry Earth - Research Only - ( Words of Material, Spirit )<BR>
This is a good spell to practice your researching on. Components for researching appear randomly on creatures that are at least the same level as the spell.. if you want Level 16 spell components, the monsters you fight will have to be at least Level 16. Assuming you succeeded in creating the spell, you'll be in for a pleasant surprise. This spell is an undead-only root spell, useful when fighting things like Undead Reavers in East Karana. Note that, like all ' root ' spells, this one has a chance to break every time a creature takes direct damage from a spell, like Ward Undead. Also note that, while spells like Heat Blood, and Leach do do damage, they aren't considered ' direct damage '. Meaning, you can stack DoTs on a root'd creature, and keep it root'd until the spells kill it, meditating throughout most of the fight. Hungry Earth also has a quaint little direct damage component.. it hits the monster for about 30. It isn't really essential.. but, it'll help you learn the in's and out's of researching.<BR>
<BR>
Shielding - Yay. You know what these spells do, by now. Run along and buy it, and expect the same upgrades.. an extra twenty or thirty points of health more than the old spell, as well as better armor and magic resistance bonuses. <BR>
<BR>
Shieldskin - ( Component: Cat's Eye Agate )<BR>
Yeah, its cool. Yeah, its kinda expensive to keep it up. Yeah, its definitely worth it. <BR>
<BR>
Situation A: ' a gnoll brawler hits YOU for 31 points of damage! '<BR>
<BR>
Ow, bish..<BR>
<BR>
Situation B: ' a gnoll brawler tries to hit you, but your magical skin absorbs the blow! '<BR>
<BR>
... Heh. Denied. <BR>
<BR>
Basically, for 2 gold, you create a magical layer of skin that absorbs about 50-80 points of damage. It won't wear off until the creature has inflicted that much damage. It also absorbs spell-damage. Making yourself as durable as possible is a good way to stay alive.. and the money really isn't that much.. I mean, gnolls drop ringmail that sells for several platinum a piece. Don't be cheap.. cheap people die.<BR>
<BR>
Spirit Armor: ' Demetrii, how come necromancer's get a Level 19 cleric buff at Level 16? '<BR>
<BR>
... Because. <BR>
<BR>
This spell will add about 17 points of armor to whoever you wanna buff. It's targetable.. stick it on your pet, and the tanks, if a cleric isn't around. It helps quite a bit.<BR>
<BR>
Restless Bones: ... ch'yeah, you -could- try to research this one ... but its better to buy the thing. The highest pet summoned by this spell can double-attack for 20, and not only does it bash.. but it also kicks. The pet has about 500 health. Pretty durable for a fleshless corpse. You can grab the scroll off of a vendor in the Paineel Shadowknight Guild.<BR>
<BR>
__________________________________________________<BR>
<BR>
By now, the gnolls are a bit too low to give good experience.. so, go to the orc gate instead. Orcs are tougher than gnolls, of course.. and they've got lots more health.. but that doesn't scare you. You're a necromancer. You -eat- things that are higher level. Your spells just don't seem to be resisted all that much, and your pet.. well, its alot tougher to resist a skeletal fist in the face.<BR>
<BR>
Be on the lookout for the Shra'lok orcs. These orcs pop up rarely, and drop some mediocre stuff. Its ' OK ' at this level, but none of it is particularly useful to a necromancer, besides the Shra'lok pack dropped by one Ghengis Shra'lok. Anything put inside this wonderful pouch weighs 25% less. Good for storing bronze weapons, and other really heavy stuff.<BR>
<BR>
Orcs'll provide you with experience all the way up to Level 20, and you'll have a chance to collect all sorts of words to play around with your research skill.. try making Banshee Aura, and Voice Graft. Graft allows you to talk through your pet.. lot's of fun. Banshee Aura surrounds you with a cool blue aura that slaps a creature for 11 points of damage whenever it decides to slap you. It does require having a Pearl in your inventory, though. Don't worry, the Pearl isn't consumed in the casting like bonechips, or Cat's Eye Agates for Shieldskin.<BR>
<BR>
Level 20: Dark Ritualist<BR>
<BR>
Hunting Grounds: Inside Highpass, Castle Mistmoore<BR>
<BR>
[ Targets will no longer be listed. I think that, by now, you've probably gotten the whole ' consider the creature before trying to kill it ' thing down. If you haven't, I'm surprised a person of such inferior intellect has managed to progress this far.. lemme guess.. E-Bay? =) ]<BR>
<BR>
Allure of Death: Oh, happy day.. oh, happy, happy day.. Dark Pact has been upstage'd by Allure of Death. This one eats about 8 health standing, and gives you 4 mana. Twice as much mana as Dark Pact.. but, it eats twice as much health. Luckily, you get a new, powerful drain at this level.. so, it all balances out.<BR>
<BR>
Siphon Life: Elite. This one sucks 65 health out of a target. Combined with Leach and Allure of Death, you'll have access to a greatly improved mana and health regeneration. Simply awsome.<BR>
<BR>
Harmshield - Research Only - ( Words of Refuge, Absorption )<BR>
This is the ' I am God ' spell. Punch it off, and you're invulnerable for 18 seconds. It also acts as a reverse taunt.. so, the creature attacks the person just above you on the hatelist. Better than Feign Death in most situations.. I mean, where's the dignity in playing possum? Its alot more fun to stand in the creature's face, and have it try repeatedly to damage you, to no avail.<BR>
<BR>
Shadow Compact: This allows you to play a much, much more effective necrohealer. Cast this on a person, and they get healed five times for twenty points every time. Of course, it drains you have 100 points of health, total.. so, just drain it back. <BR>
<BR>
Shadow Vortex: Its like a Lifedrain, only for armor. Cast it on a creature, and they lose 13 AC. You gain it. Not a bad tradeoff.<BR>
<BR>
Animate Dead: Kinda hard to find the spell, unless you know where to look.. it is sold in the Paineel shadowknight guild. The pet is becoming pretty deadly. Punching for 22, and kicking and bashing for about 12, it can dole out death pretty quickly, with your spells backing it up. Its also got around 650 health.<BR>
<BR>
__________________________________________________<BR>
<BR>
Highpass still offers experience, but the inconvenience of not being able to sell unless you've managed to raise your merchant faction enough is.. well.. an inconvenience.. and, the experience isn't all that great anymore.. so, do what I did.<BR>
<BR>
Grab some wizard, and order them to transport you to Greater Faydark. Once there, find Lesser Faydark, and jog along the right zonewall, invisible, until you find, at long last, a set of stonehenge-like ruins. They have a big red rune on them, and resemble druid teleport rings. They've also got a bunch of fae drakes flapping around them. Run into the canyon directly behind these, and bind yourself here.<BR>
__________________________________________________<BR>
<BR>
Welcome to Mistmoore<BR>
<BR>
Grab a group for the Hill, or Cove, and get ready for ridiculous amounts of experience. I went from Level 20 - 22 in a day. This zone has an experience bonus of about 15%.. meaning, you get about 15% extra experience per kill here. The spawns are fast and furious, and the loot is quite good.. gargoyle eyes sell for around 10 platinum. Fine steel and bronze drops here, as well as spell research components, and best of all, the creatures are all rogues, and wizards! They die ludicrously quickly in a good group.<BR>
<BR>
Even better, there are 13 - 16 spawns that your group can have access to on a slow day. The coin is nice here, too.. and rawhide drops are quite frequent. Its safe to stay here for a good, long time. I went from 20 - 30 in no time, flat. The fights are ussually exciting, and the spellcasting creatures are quite a bit more deadly here.. the wizards can throw a spell that blasts 200 points of health off of your tank. Ouch.<BR>
<BR>
The only problem here is the blatant hostility of the races of Faydwer. Dwarves hate you.. elves hate you.. heck, even those ' stylish ' gnomes hate you.. <BR>
<BR>
However, it turns out those gnomes are good for something, after all. You see, gnomes hate you.. but not that much. They'd like you better if you murdered minotaurs, so go do that. Waste Minotaurs in the Minotaur caves until you grow so mind-numbingly bored that you cringe if someone even mentions the half-bull, low-green jerks.<BR>
<BR>
If you're lucky, the guards will be dubious.. or even apprehensive. No need to worry about selling to the dubious vendors in Ak'anon, though.. they've got a cleverly concealed, wonderfully indifferent mechanical merchant right next to the Minotaur Caves. Facing the caves, turn to look to your left. You'll see a big gear, toppled over, flat on the ground. Hop into the middle of it, and there'll be a vendor there.<BR>
<BR>
This is also a good time to trade out your backpacks for Toolboxes. Toolboxes have the same weight, and number of inventory slots.. but, they can hold Giant size items, like Halberds. Backpacks can't claim that.<BR>
<BR>
Just in case there is something in Ak'anon that just doesn't like you, run invisible through the town, and drop invisibility in the bank. Then, Gate back to Mistmoore. Once you hit Level 24, you have a few more options on places to hunt, but Mistmoore is still giving extremely good experience, and a conveniently nearby place to sell.. so, I wouldn't recommend leaving until 30, or 31.<BR>
<BR>
Level 24: Tormentor of Souls<BR>
<BR>
Hunting Grounds: Inside Highpass, Castle Mistmoore, Estate of Unrest<BR>
<BR>
Breath of the Dead - Research Only - ( Words of Cloudburst, Mistbreath, Cazic-Thule )<BR>
Take up fishing. Mistmoore has a pond, as I'm sure you know if you've been hunting there. Fish out of the pond, and gather fish scales. This spell consumes 1 fish scale, and allows you to breath underwater for about 45 minutes. Great for maxing out your swimming skill.<BR>
<BR>
Intensify Death - Research Only - ( Words of the Sentient - Beza - ,Recluse, Absorption )<BR>
This is a must-have spell, although the duration isn't particularly good. This spell gives your pet 22% haste at Level 24, and eventually maxes out at 30%. It also gives your pet +30 strength, and about 10 points of extra armor class. Use it frequently.. you'll definitely notice a difference.<BR>
<BR>
Shadowsight - Alot of people think this one is research-only. It isn't. Keep this in mind.. if shadowknights get the spell, then the spell is buyable. Meaning, our Level 29, 39, and 44 pets are buyable at many Shadowknight guilds. Shadowknights don't get the Research skill. This particular spell is the upgrade to deadeye.. it seems to have a shorter duration, but it doesn't cost much to cast.. so.. <BR>
<BR>
It replaces Infravision with the superior Ultravision, and has the familiar See Invisible effect that we know and love. It turns night into day. You can buy it at the Paineel Shadowknight Guild.<BR>
<BR>
Haunting Corpse - Research Only - ( Words of Possession, Detachment, Allure )<BR>
This spell marks a turning point in a necromancer's life. The skeleton turns brown, signifying the terrifying metamorphosis taking place. The pet is faster, tougher, stronger, and much more effective from this point on. This spell can generate a skeleton that is anywhere from Level 18 - 22.. and the pet punches for a maximum of 26.<BR>
<BR>
Leatherskin - The upgrade to Shieldskin, this spell requires a more expensive Bloodstone to cast. The skin created can absorb about 125 points of damage. Very nice.<BR>
<BR>
Major Shielding - Adding about 70 points of extra health, 20 points of armor class, and about 15 points of magic resistance, this spell is far superior to Shielding. <BR>
<BR>
Rapacious Subversion - Lots of people count this useless at low levels.. but, if the healer is completely out of mana, and the necromancer is at full.. and the tank is severely injured.. the necromancer can cast this until he runs out of mana, injecting mana into the healer, and negating downtime. Of course, being out of mana isn't a problem for a necromancer.. just turn on Allure of Death, and meditate it back up.<BR>
<BR>
Scent of Shadow - This is the first effective resistance debuff that necromancers get.. and all of our debuffs are actually useful to us. This one knocks off about 15 points of fire, disease, and poison resistance, and it looks pretty elite with the new spell animations.<BR>
<BR>
Screaming Terror - One of the most overlooked spells in a necromancer's arsenal.. we get yet another ability from a completely different class.. the ability to effectively control crowds. This spell ' mesmerizes ' a creature, and has a 50% chance of clearing its hatelist. The mesmerization effect makes the creature stand still, and do absolutely nothing. It lasts for 18 seconds, or until the creature takes damage. <BR>
<BR>
Note that while the creature cannot take damage, it can be debuff'd with a strength-lowering spell, a resistance debuff, and a Slow spell cast by an enchanter or shaman. Then, you can wake the creature up with a DoT spell, and let the tanks annihilate it. <BR>
<BR>
Its main use in a group is when the tank gets two or more creatures, and he can't take them all on at once. You cast this spell on the two that he isn't fighting, and they stop attacking, allowing the tank and your pet to kill the creatures, one by one. A bit expensive to cast at this level, but very useful.<BR>
<BR>
Shock of Poison - Finally, a direct damage spell! Slow-casting, and inefficient compared to a wizard's spell.. but nonetheless deadly. It deals 146 points of damage at level 24, and maxes out at 160 by level 29. If your DoT isn't killing the creature fast enough, or if the tank is severely wounded, and the creature is still at about half-health, throwing this at the target once or twice should turn the tide.<BR>
<BR>
__________________________________________________<BR>
<BR>
You should make a habit of constantly auctioning for the particular words you need for the Level that you're in, and once you get them, you should not try to research the spell.. rather, you should find a higher level necromancer with 100+ research skill, and have him or her make the spell. They have almost no chance of failing, and doing without the Level 24 pet is not good at all.<BR>
<BR>
You have several options available to you at Level 24. With your new spells, you'll be able to dominate in a group on the Hill or Cove, playing the part of healer, crowd controller, and nuker if the need arises. Heck, your pet could probably be the group's tank. All the monsters will be blue to you, which is ideal, as most of your spells will go through.. Mistmoore is heaven at Level 24 - 29.<BR>
<BR>
However, if you want a change of scenery.. you could get teleported back to North Karana, and head over to Highpass for basement goblins. <BR>
<BR>
-Why- the Highpass Fortress has goblins living in its basement, I do not know. I do know that the goblins will be much higher level than the familiars you've been fighting in Mistmoore.. and they drop useful research words, as well as fine steel, and pieces of bronze armor, rarely.<BR>
<BR>
Furthermore, there are vendors and a bank in the same zone. You won't have enough faction to sell, however.. so, start collecting Goblin ears. When you get four, give all four of them in a stack to the Captain Bosec. He hangs around the entrance to the basement, and sometimes wanders into the bank if he chased a runaway goblin there. For each ear, you get better faction with the guards and the vendors. It'll take about 100 ears to get the ability to sell here.. but you do get around 8 gold per ear from the Captain, too.  Its not that bad.<BR>
<BR>
If you don't want to make the run back to Highpass right now, no big deal. You can hang around in Mistmoore, as the Graveyard is open to you in a balanced group, and the Pit is open to you at Level 26, even though everything will be quite red to you.<BR>
<BR>
The Graveyard spawns pretty nasty stuff, and things can be up to Level 30 at times.. but you'll level so quickly that you'll be within casting range of the highest creatures in no time. Note that the monsters here aren't rogues. The warders and custodians are Clerics.. and nasty clerics, too. They can blast you for 200 at times, and heal themselves for 300. Make -sure- to interrupt them when they try to heal themselves. Screaming Terror will interrupt a spell, assuming it goes through on a creature that cons red to you. Your pet's bashes and kicks might manage to interrupt them as well. Sentries and guards are standard warriors.. they've got lots of health compared to the familiars, which were all rogues and wizards.. but, a few DoTs, a DD, and a tough tank.. and you'll be fine.<BR>
<BR>
The Pit is a different story. The stuff here hits hard, has tons of health, and everything spawns rather closely together. The experience and loot -cannot- be beaten. The excitement can't be beaten, either. Truly a wonderful experience, the groups here will be rather high level compared to you, but you will get fine experience. I joined my first pit group at Level 26, and just about every spell went through. Our DD is poison-based, and creatures generally have low poison resistance.. so my DD was actually effective. Heat Blood goes through on deep red cons anyway.. and our Drains aren't resisted at all. The pet will be contributing hundreds of points of damage per fight, so you'll be pulling your own weight. The monsters here are ancilles.. Platemail-wearing fiends that double for 70's. Don't get aggro'd.. and if you do, Harmshield or feign, and hope for the best. They'll cut right through you like a hot knife through butter.<BR>
<BR>
Last but not least, and nowhere near as effective a leveling spot as Mistmoore or Highpass, is the Estate of Unrest.<BR>
<BR>
Nestled in Verant's elaborate practical joke of a zone called Dagnor's Cauldron, the Estate of Unrest -is- frequently hunted in.. however, most of the groups do the yard trash. Granted, there are much higher nasties inside the House itself, no one seems to be particularly interested in it. Its tough to find a group high enough to go deep inside the House, but when you do, its almost as cool as the Pit.<BR>
<BR>
First, let me say that this is the place to go if you're low on bonechips. This place has legions and legions and battalions and hoardes of skeletons.. and the ones outside are all low green. You're pet can solo them. <BR>
<BR>
The skeletons inside range from blue cons on the first floor that make for good hunting, to the nasty red barb boned, and drybone skeletons on the second and third floor. A group of Level 25s could toast the first floor, and probably a good portion of the second. Best of all, Invisibility to Undead will protect you from 99% of the creatures here.. except for another of Verant's practical jokes. The werebat. <BR>
<BR>
About as unintimidating as a werewolf, they aren't taller than 2', and they look alot like tiny chimpanzees.. except they have the face of a bat, and glowing red eyes. They aren't undead, either.. and they see right through invisibility.. and they hate you.. and they attack very fast. Getting attacked means ' bye bye Invisibility to Undead '.. and that means everything on the floor is going to want to murder you. If your group is going to do Unrest, spot the Werebats first, and kill them.<BR>
<BR>
Aside from Werebats, you'll find ghouls, and carrion ghouls.. carrion ghouls are just higher level ghouls. Ghouls are -obviously- undead goblins. Just as annoying as a normal goblin, but far deadlier, a Ghoul employs Ghoulroot. It sticks you to the ground while the ghoul clobbers you. <BR>
<BR>
How endearing.<BR>
<BR>
Last but not least, if you are around 27 or 28, and your group is tough.. several tanks, and a healer or two.. the Basement is fine. You'll be encountering the same stuff that you'd find on the second floor, with the addition of  ' Festering Hags '. <BR>
<BR>
These things just suck. They're HP is nothing.. the amount of damage they do, however, is mind-boggling. BOOM. The tank loses 232 health. Just like that. They're level 30ish wizards, and killing them as quickly as possible by showering them with Undead-Only direct damage ( ... you -did- practice evocation, right? ) is the name of the game. If you were a FREAKING IDIOT and didn't practice your evocation like I told you to, Shock of Poison'll do. Take advantage of their low HP, and of course have a pet made so that it'll contribute.<BR>
<BR>
These are the three spots that're on the top of the list for experience gain, in my opinion. There might be others, but this is what I did, and my played time at Level 44 is 14 days.. which isn't bad at all. Of course, Kunark offers some nice spots.. but Firionia Vie hates you, and so do the Iksar.. and getting a port every time you need to sell is inconvenient. Inconveniences slow down leveling.<BR>
<BR>
Level 29: Practitioner of Herecies<BR>
<BR>
Hunting Grounds: Frontier Mountains( Knrk. ), Mistmoore, Highpass, Tower of Frozen Shadow ( Vel. )<BR>
<BR>
Boil Blood - Nasty, but slow, Boil Blood is the much-needed, eagerly anticipated upgrade to Heat Blood. This one does more damage per tick, but still takes a very long time to wear off. Twenty-one ticks, in fact. Still, it is very difficult to resist, and for 150 points of mana, you get a maximum damage of 505. Extremely useful when soloing.<BR>
<BR>
Dismiss Undead - Yet another Undead direct damage spell. Nice, depending on the situation.<BR>
<BR>
Dooming Darkness - This is the one to use when soloing, although it is rather expensive to cast, and a pain when it is resisted. 150 mana gets you a 300 damage DoT, with a snare effect of 60%. Not only does it last awhile, but it also does considerable damage at this point. Definitely pick this one up, as most people prefer using it at Level 49.. it is cheaper than Cascading Darkness, and has about the same snare effect.. although Cascading does DoT for 1152.<BR>
<BR>
Renew Bones - Research Only - ( Words of Purification, Incorporeal, Acquisition - Azia - )<BR>
This will make soloing that much easier. If your pet is running dangerously low on health, this spell will heal it for a huge amount of health. Again, no aggro buildup.. but the recast delay on this one always has to be taken into consideration. <BR>
<BR>
Spirit Tap - A sickeningly good upgrade to Siphon Life, Spirit Tap sucks 132 points of health out of a creature, and gives it to you. Truly a mind-boggling amount, this was enough to heal me for over a bubble of health at that Level. <BR>
<BR>
Vampiric Curse - Buyable in several shadowknight guilds, this one is better than Spirit Tap, and dwarfs the amount of health that Leach was draining. Vampiric Curse drains 187 points of health over time, effectively bestowing a 37 point a tick regeneration effect on you when you're sitting down. You can stick Allure of Death on yourself, and still get tons of health every six seconds. It is a wonderful, wonderful spell.<BR>
<BR>
Summon Dead - Again, because Shadowknights get this spell at 49, we can buy it. This spell creates a pet that dual-wields.. Meaning, it sometimes gets an extra attack by attacking with its other hand. However, you need to give it two one-handed weapons before it activates this ability. Keep a supply of rusty daggers on hand.. they're cheap, and they'll do in a pinch. This pet has about 900 health, and can punch for a maximum of three hits of 29. <BR>
__________________________________________________<BR>
<BR>
At this point, you've got lots of options available to you. You'll be extremely effective in Pit groups, the Graveyard will provide fine experience, and you'll be able to contribute alot more to groups there, and if you've been hanging out at Highpass, and the vendors are selling to you, you've got another option available to you.<BR>
<BR>
Pickclaw Warrior groups. <BR>
<BR>
The warriors aren't as nasty as the ancilles in Mistmoore, but the groups that hunt them tend to be in the high twenties to mid-thirties. Pickclaw warriors aren't particularly tough. They die too quickly for Boil Blood to be effective, though, and darkness is resisted waaay to much to cast frequently. <BR>
<BR>
I'd suggest sticking Vampiric Curse, sicking the pet, and throwing a Shock of Poison to ensure your contribution of 300-400+ points of damage that fight. The longer-lasting DoTs just don't get to stick to the creature long enough to do significant damage, meaning you're just wasting mana for the most part. The group might also decide to grab the spawns in the ' Raider ' room. Raiders, and seers pop up there, besides the goblins that you're used to. Raiders are just a level or two higher than warriors, and seers are just a bit tougher than Visionaries. Nothing too nasty, but if the spawn isn't broken, and the puller gets all three, it is a good time to make use of Screaming Terror. Make sure to notify the group that you'll be mesmerizing stuff.. unless, of course, there is an enchanter on hand.<BR>
<BR>
If you're the adventurous type, and you have the expansions downloaded, now is a good time to try your hand at the more exciting, more dangerous lands of Kunark and Velious. <BR>
<BR>
.. Yes, Necromancers can hang around at Velious at Level 29. If I can do it, you can do it.<BR>
<BR>
First off, Frontier Mountains offers an interesting experience, in the form of Giant hunting, and Molemen groups. You could either grab a teleport to the Dreadlands, and follow the left wall until you find, at very, very long last, the zone to Frontier Mountains.. ( ... not to be confused with the zoneline to Burning Woods.. )or, alternatively, you could hitch a ride on the boat, travel to the elven outpost of Firionia Vie, which you're very KoS to, and sneak through the place, invisible. Leaping off the boat before it reaches the docks is a must. I always took the Dreadland route, and you should too. Its just more convenient.<BR>
<BR>
Be careful, because things in the Dreadlands.. like Drolvargs, for instance.. see right through Invisibility. They hate you, and they're red. Don't fall off the mountain sides, either. You'll take hundreds of points of damage, at times.<BR>
<BR>
Once you reach the Frontier Mountains, follow the right wall until you reach the zoneline to the Lake of Ill Omen. Bind yourself here, and run, invisible, straight ahead. You'll go over a big mountain, and just behind the mountain, you'll see a fort. Avoiding the mountain giants, which handily see right through invisibility.. ( .. even though the significantly higher level Hill Giants don't .. go figure )make your way to the area just before the entrance, and join a group. The loot is heavy, but fantastic.<BR>
<BR>
At about 30, the first real Hell Level, you'll be ready for moles. Run straight down the slope, with your back to the Ill Omen zoneline, and stop when you enter the ravine. Follow the ravine right, and you'll eventually get to a hill with a cave in the side. There'll probably be a group here, and there'll be plenty of  ' Burynai '. Disturbingly adoreable, they make pathetic little rodent noises when you murder them. They're such great fun.<BR>
<BR>
Finally, you could go to the Northern Desert of Ro, back on Antonica, and follow the shoreline until you find a dock, with a gnome beside it. Wait until a skiff arrives, and hop aboard.. the skiff'll drop you off on an island in the Iceclad Ocean. Immediately run straight ahead, across the island, and locate the much bigger, infinitely more conspicuous Icebreaker dock. It has big.. rock things.. jutting out of it.<BR>
<BR>
When the boat arrives, hop aboard, and it'll ferry you over to the Velious mainland. Run ahead, and follow the shoreline to the left.. and stay invisible, because the wandering stuff here will eat you for breakfast. Bind yourself at the gnomish encampment that you'll run across.. ( .. look for the pirate sentries .. )and keep going.<BR>
<BR>
You'll eventually locate a biiiiig tower.. with lots of shadow guardians floating and swirling around it. They can't see invisible, so just run towards the tower. You'll see a weird, upside-down triangle mirror on the side of the tower, near the base. Click it, and it'll zone you into the tower. <BR>
<BR>
Now, for the risky, but amusing part.<BR>
<BR>
Whip out Dominate Undead. Locate a Shadowbone skeleton, and Dominate it. If it resists, feign death. Keep dominating until you get that friggin' skeleton. When the spell sticks, the skeleton becomes your temporary pet. A pet that hits for 56. Elite.<BR>
<BR>
Now, if there were any other skeletons standing near it, they'll jump their buddy. One skeleton fighting your ' pet ' is ideal. Let your pet get beat up, but help him out. His opponent should drop dead, but he should be severely injured. Now's the fun part. Cast Cancel Magic on him, to make the Dominate wear off prematurely, if it didn't already, and then stick him with Hungry Earth. Boil Blood, and Vampiric Curse to regain any lost health. Two big chunks of experience, just like that.. and, these suckers drop several platinum at times. They also drop Velium weapons at times.. and up to 4 bone chips. If a ' large undead gnoll ' spawns, avoid him like the plague. He owns you. If you pull a train, feign. Or, zone. Be ready to run when you zone, though.. because the shadow guardians'll jump you, an' they hurt. <BR>
<BR>
A risky place to hunt.. but, if you are confident in your skills, it can be done. <BR>
<BR>
Once you get out of Level 30, the experience should fly.<BR>
<BR>
Level 34: Invoker of Shadows<BR>
<BR>
Hunting Grounds: Frontier Mountains, Dreadlands, The Overthere, Eastern Wastes, Highpass, Great Divide<BR>
<BR>
Call of Bones - Research Only - ( Words of Motion, Neglect, Endurance )<BR>
... and, with this spell, enchanters that aren't Level 50+ become obsolete. Transforming you into a skeleton, and granting you Ultravision are two of the three effects of this awsome spell. The third effect is the fact that you gain more mana per tick than Clarity. Unfortunately, Vampiric Curse can barely keep up with it. This sucks 15 points of HP standing, and 12 sitting. It really, really hurts. Slowly, you'll get used to it. Just Spirit Tap when necessary, and, in a group setting, don't be afraid to allow yourself to get a bit low.. about two bubbles of health.. before tapping it all back.<BR>
<BR>
Greater Shielding - ... Just a standard upgrade to the well-known line of caster buffs. Nice MR, Nice HP, Nice AC. No reason not to have it on all the time.<BR>
<BR>
Steelskin - Yippie-kiy-yay. Grab the Jaspers. This one is the real deal, folks. Over 200 points of damage will be absorbed by this puppy before the beasty actually manages to lay one dirty finger on you. Not really expensive to keep on. About a platinum piece per gemstone.<BR>
<BR>
Invoke Fear - Possibly Research Only - ( Words of Resolve, Quivering, Duration )<BR>
I'm almost positive shadowknight guilds carry this, even though I researched it. I mean, if it isn't carried in any shadowknight guilds, then it's the only spell in the game that actually requires a shadowknight to go and seek out a researcher. Anywho, I'll give you the scoop on the spell. It's an abso-friggin'-lute necessity to -any- necromancer. Find this one in -advance-, before you hit 34. Hope you've been doing that with all your spells. Whereas Fear lasts for a maximum amount of 18 seconds, Invoke Fear sticks for up to 42 seconds. The spell is a wee bit expensive, but with the intelligence enhancers, raw mana boosts, and your sickeningly high base intelligence, you'll probably be able to recast as many times as you need during most combats. 120 mana gets you a spell that casts twice as quickly as Fear, with much less resists, and a potential duration that's more than twice as long as its nasty predecessor. <BR>
<BR>
Invoke Shadow - Research Only - ( Words of Dark Paths, Haunting, Suffering ) <BR>
Dark Paths was a toughy to find, but the other two were easy to come buy. This can create a pet with a maximum Level of 30. The pet can punch for 33. It automatically dual-wields now, so you don't need to give it weapons. It does look cooler if you do, though. The pet can take a beating, with a maximum health capacity that exceeds 1200. <BR>
<BR>
Root - ... finally. <BR>
<BR>
I mean, Necromancers are quite capable of playing the shaman game of root, and Damage over Time. We're much better at it, too. Our DoTs have higher damage rates, and they're much more efficient. Our DDs heal us, and we regenerate mana faster than most enchanters. <BR>
<BR>
Fact is, we aren't really -suited- for the tactic. I can't really.. explain it. Maybe it's just me, but when I try the root and DoT tactic out, I feel.. empty. Necromancers tell skeletons to murder people, and convince those people to be terrified, so that they never have a chance to fight back. <BR>
<BR>
We don't glue people to the ground, and meditate. Heck, I don't even keep this spell mem'd. Useless in PvP against smart people, too. I mean, who doesn't have 60+ MR during a duel? If they don't, then you don't need root to beat them. They're so dumb that your pet alone could probably deal with them.<BR>
<BR>
Venom of the Snake - &quot;... Welcome home, Poison Bolt! My, how you've grown ...! &quot;<BR>
<BR>
Yes, yes, yes. If you know the statistics on this spell, you're probably wearing a stupid grin, and your eyes are taking on a twinkle that's downright unhealthy.<BR>
<BR>
If you don't, allow me to enlighten you. <BR>
<BR>
160 mana gives you a Damage over Time spell that nails the target for 40 points of damage, initially. Every six seconds, they take about 70 points of damage, until the combined damage of seven ticks reaches roughly 450. <BR>
<BR>
To put it bluntly, this spell eats things. It does so in 42 seconds. Fast, and deadly. It gets resisted a bit, but not all that much. After all, it's poison based. NPCs seem to conveniently forget about having good poison resistance.<BR>
<BR>
It builds monstrous aggro, so wait for a little while in a group setting. <BR>
<BR>
In a solo situation, the target is fear'd. Who cares about aggro?<BR>
<BR>
Resist Disease - Yet another shaman line of spells rendered ineffective against you. Great for duels.. and not much else. It boosts disease resistance by about 40 points. Shaman trying to Scourge you? <BR>
<BR>
I don't think so.<BR>
__________________________________________________<BR>
<BR>
The choices are up to you. A group in the Dreadlands for the North Wall at Karnor's Castle? A Pickclaw Warrior Group at Highpass? Perhaps you'd like to casually solo Mountain Giants in the Frontier Mountains? Or, do you prefer the cold climes of Velious? <BR>
<BR>
The Eastern Wastes can be reached by facing out from the Iceclad docks, and following the shoreline left. Avoid everything you see, and after a very long run, you'll find a huge dragonbone bridge with two Frost Giants standing next to it. You -can- solo these, but it's rather tough. A few resists, and you simply wont have enough mana to finish them off. You can solo in the Eastern Wastes.. Stick mainly to Dire Wolves, Mammoths, and Dervishes.<BR>
<BR>
Everything in Velious has obscene amounts of health, so even you might be low on mana after the fights. It is definitely best to seek a group until you're a bit higher. Ry'Gorr Orcs are the perfect solution. <BR>
<BR>
Running straight out from the Bridge, and veering off just a tad to the right will bring you to a fortress with a column of smoke rising from a campfire in its center. Remaining invisible, just jog around the perimeter, find the entrance, and back up. People ussually set up groups here, and pull from inside the fort. <BR>
<BR>
To get to the Great Divide, and locate a city that'll like you a bit more than what you might be used to, run off of the Bridge, and follow the shoreline right. Keep going for.. quite awhile.. passing walruses, and walrus-men known as Ulthorks. Keep on running, and you'll reach the zoneline. Big mountains. <BR>
<BR>
Follow the mountain range left, and you'll come upon a canyon. Pass through it, and you'll enter the Great Divide. <BR>
<BR>
Nothing you encounter on your trip to Thurgadin will see through invisibility. Ignore the frost giants, and drakkel dire wolves, and follow the zonewall left. Keep on running, until you reach a stream. Facing the side of the stream, with your back facing the direction of the Eastern Wastes Canyon, follow the stream right. You'll see hunting wolves, which are quite friendly, and the Coldain dwarves, which are apprehensive. Don't kill any of the hunting wolves, or dwarves. Cherish your dwarf faction. The little bluebeards rock. So do their quests.<BR>
<BR>
Bind yourself in the Thurgadin Bank, and find groups for Kodiaks. They're big bears that are easily Fear-Kite'd in groups. To find their caves, leave Thurgadin, keeping the waterfall at your back. Follow the right wall, and you'll eventually find a series of caves. The very last cave you find is the one most heavily camped. It has so many blue to red-con spawns that your head will spin. You'll be out of hell in no time, assuming you're 35.<BR>
<BR>
If you choose Kunark, you can ask around for the Overthere zoneline. Once inside, tackle Sarnaks and Cacti.. and Cockatrices.. and.. well.. maybe the Rhinos, although they can outrun Spirit of Wolf. If Darkness doesn't stick, sick your pet on them, and recast it. If it doesn't stick that time, just feign death. Let the pet build aggro, and try again. Or, if you like, flee. Everything else is easily fear-kite'd.<BR>
<BR>
Bounce through the levels with your new spells. 34 to 39 is rather easily done. Take some time to enjoy your spells, and smell the corp-- err, roses.<BR>
<BR>
Level 39: Malignant Revelations<BR>
<BR>
Hunting Grounds: Velious, Velious, Velious.<BR>
<BR>
Augment Death - ... haaaahahahahaha ... sick, sick, sick. Intensify Death never really got much use, because I hated having to recast it so frequently, and it had a horrendous recast delay. Augment Death has the same recast delay, but it sticks on your pet for 15 minutes. <BR>
<BR>
It starts out as a 49% Haste, and works its way up to 55% by Level 45. It also gives about 50 points of strength, and 20 points of armor class. Keep this on your pet at all times.<BR>
<BR>
Drain Spirit - Yum. 200+ points of Drain'd health. Need we say more? Hey, it's even mana efficient! It deals more damage than it costs in mana! Yaaaay!<BR>
<BR>
Expel Undead - Bang. 265ish Damage to the Undead. *Yawn*<BR>
<BR>
Nullify Magic - Yummy in duels. It has a better chance to dispel an effect, and it can dispel up to two effects, whereas cancel only hits one.<BR>
<BR>
Summon Corpse - Dropped in Splitpaw - For the cost of a 175pp component that can't be stacked, this spell instantly teleports the corpse(s) of the targeted player to your feet, no matter how far away the corpse(s) are. Very useful on raids, but not at this point. The raids you're going on probably have fairly straightforward Corpse Retrievals. It is still nice to have it in the book, though. <BR>
<BR>
Scourge - A much more easily-resisted Boil Blood, with a DD component, so it has a chance to break roots! Yay! It does about 500 damage over two minutes, but at higher levels, it can be used on the beefy creatures you're kiting, to throw in some extra damage.<BR>
<BR>
Scent of Darkness - The best resistance debuff we get 'til the deep 50s. It nails fire, disease, and poison resistance for about 30 points of debuff. Nice, right before you toss Venoms and Scourges.<BR>
<BR>
Malignant Dead - Nasty, nasty, nasty. This pet has roughly 1400 points of health, occasionally hits for 39 points of damage, and bashes and kicks for around 15 or 16 each. With Augment Death on, it is a skeletal war machine. It is also buyable in shadowknight guilds. Lucky you.<BR>
__________________________________________________<BR>
<BR>
Kunark does have viable hunting spots, but Firionia Vie faction just.. isn't your bag. Velious has better loot, better experience, and.. well.. better everything. The dwarves like you, so you can sell. The area you're hunting in is one zone away from the city, too. <BR>
<BR>
I mean.. convenience is a beautiful thing.<BR>
<BR>
Nothing much to say here. Scourge is useless in a group setting.. worse than Boil Blood, 'cause it costs more, and gets resisted much more often. I mean.. really, aside from looking at the cool green swirls that you got with your Level 39 animations.. <BR>
<BR>
Venom of the Snake gives you the same cheap thrill of green, swirly thingies.. it works better, it is resisted less often, it costs less mana. Don't use Scourge. Ever. <BR>
<BR>
You're pet is a very, very viable damage dealer. No reason not to have your pet out. Use him constantly. He is useful in just about any situation. Kodiaks can be done, solo or in a group, until 44. You can do some Wurms, and Ry'Gorr Orcs if you're getting bored with the craptacular loot on the bears.. but, aside from that, Velious is your home.<BR>
<BR>
Level 44: The Darkness Becomes You<BR>
<BR>
Hunting Grounds: Great Divide, Eastern Wastes, Velketor's Labyrinth<BR>
<BR>
Arch Shielding - Yay. The last version of shielding until you rise above the 50th Level Barrier. <BR>
<BR>
Diamondskin - Well, this one costs a horrendous amount of platinum to use. I ussually keep about five or six Peridots on me, for special occasions. Steelskin is for everyday use. Diamondskin's component costs about ten times more.<BR>
<BR>
Cackling Bones - The skeleton is now taller than you, hits for a maximum of 47, and occasionally processes a Lifedrain that hits for about 20. It kicks and bashes for 19. It has about 1700 health. Augmented, it is very, very deadly. It is also buyable.<BR>
<BR>
Covetous Subversion - Well, you can transfer mana with the same efficiency of a Manastone. You also transfer mana in much greater amounts. Why not buy the spell?<BR>
<BR>
Dead Man Floating - Research Only - ( Words of Burnishing, Psyche ) <BR>
The spell duration is 72 minutes. It grants the target See Invisibility, Levitation, Water Breathing, and +70ish Poison Resistance. It is research-only, but it is worth it. A wonderful spell, and you can even cast it on other people.<BR>
<BR>
Asystole - The upgrade to Heartflutter. It lowers the strength of the Target by about 40, hits their AC for 20, and DoTs them for nearly 700 damage, in one minute and eighteen seconds. It is disease-based, so it is rather nice in duels, too. A very long casting time, and a fairly hefty mana cost are its downsides. Still, it has an efficiency that is better than 3 to 1. I love the spell, personally. As usual, the Heart Flutter line is a huge taunt, so wait a bit before you cast it in a group situation.<BR>
<BR>
Ignite Bones - Your evocation is up to snuff, right? You practiced with your Ward line throughout the levels, didn't you? This one is Evocation. However, it isn't Undead Only. It is a fire-based, all or nothing blast of 494 - 500, and it makes the target look like a brown skeleton for about eighteen seconds. Use it primarily on raids, when the damage needs to be done right now. <BR>
__________________________________________________<BR>
<BR>
Well, you've been murdering Kodiaks for some time, now. Same with orcs, and probably even wurms. The orcs are still an option, but I'd do them solo. They're simple with your new DoT, and your new pet. Just Dooming Darkness, Invoke Fear, Asystole. The pet takes care of the rest. <BR>
<BR>
However, if you want Faction with both Dragons and the Coldain, run along the wall, heading towards the Eastern Wastes canyon. Facing the Zoneline to the Wastes, turn left. You'll see a tree. Park your pet there, and solo Giants.<BR>
<BR>
Have a Spirit of Wolf on, just in case. Giants do social, and they also help out the dire wolves. Dire wolves help out giants, too, so be careful with your pulls.<BR>
<BR>
Frost Giants have tons of health, and they hit fairly hard. They're easily Fearkited, however, so do just that. Ignite Bones really hurts them, and everything on Velious has low fire resistance, anywho. Just to be safe, you can drop a Scent of Darkness on them. Normally, the pet, a Dooming Darkness, Asystole, and a single Ignite Bones is enough to take down a scout. You can meditate in Boneform throughout the fight, standing to recast Invoke Fear. Darkness almost never wears off. Remember to keep Augment Death on the pet.<BR>
<BR>
If you're out for experience, and not faction or loot, just solo the Kodiaks. Ignite Bones pretty much murders these. One casting, and your pet will do the rest.<BR>
<BR>
However, if you want a shot at getting gemstones for your Thurgadin Questarmor, head straight up the wall from Kodiak Cave 3, and you'll see a big cave entrance. Run inside, and find the zone to Velketor's Labyrinth. Everything here is going to be yellow, and red to you. The groups'll be made up of high levels, so you'll have quite a good time. It'll be just like the Pit was at Level 26, but your spells'll be more effective.<BR>
<BR>
The Spiders and Statues here have ungodly amounts of health. Don't bother Blasting them. Just stick Asystole on them, and pray they don't aggro you. If they do, Harmshield. These things don't mess around.<BR>
<BR>
The levels after 44 are a pain, but keep on going. Don't be intimidated by the super-slow Level 45. If you stick with it, it will go away as well.<BR>
<BR>
__________________________________________________<BR>
